ANC deputy President, David Mabuza, is now a member of parliament! Mabuza was sworn in as a Member of Parliament (MP) on Tuesday by Chief Justice, Mogoeng Mogoeng, at the Presidential guest house, Sefako Makgatho in Tshwane. President Cyril Ramaphosa, Speaker of the National Assembly, Thandi Modise and ANC Chief Whip, Pemmy Majodina joined Mabuza as he was sworn in. After the swearing in, Mabuza was congratulated by the President who shook his hand and said “Siphelele manje”. Mabuza was not sworn-in with other members of parliament as his swearing in was postponed. At the time Ramaphosa said Mabuza had postponed his swearing-in to deal with the ANC’s  Integrity Commission report on him. The Integrity commission had red-flagged Mabuza and other party figures as not suitable to represent the governing ANC in parliament The Deputy President had indicated he would like to have an opportunity to address the Integrity Commission on those allegations. Mabuza has cleared his name before the commission and is ready to serve.He appeared before the commission on Friday where he defended himself against accusations of corruption. He is now expected to be appointed as deputy president of the country when the president announces his cabinet. Former Minister of Home Affairs, Malusi Gigaba and former Speaker of the National Assembly Baleka Mbete’ have since resigned from the list of ANC MPs. Nomvula Mokonyane will also not be the Chair of Chairs.